      "source": [
        "## 6.21 Recursive algorithms and bounded memory\n",
        "\n",
        "The covariance equation\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Gamma_n\\phi_n=\\gamma_n\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is conceptually clear, but it has a problem: as $n$ grows, the system changes size. Solving a new $n\\times n$ system from scratch at every time step is expensive.\n",
        "\n",
        "This motivates recursive forecasting algorithms:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Durbin--Levinson algorithm** solves Toeplitz systems efficiently and is central for AR prediction.\n",
        "- **Innovations algorithm** updates forecasts using new innovations.\n",
        "- **Kalman filter** performs recursive prediction and updating for state-space models.\n",
        "- **Particle filters** extend filtering ideas to nonlinear and non-Gaussian state-space models.\n",
        "\n",
        "These algorithms all follow a common pattern:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\text{new forecast} = \\text{old forecast} + \\text{correction from new information}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This pattern will return in later chapters when we discuss state-space models, hidden Markov models, and recurrent neural networks.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6.22 Forecasting after transformations\n",
        "\n",
        "Many time series are not stationary on the original scale. Suppose\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "X_t=\\mu_t+Y_t,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $\\mu_t$ is trend/seasonality and $Y_t$ is stationary. A common strategy is:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. estimate $\\mu_t$;\n",
        "2. compute residuals $\\widehat Y_t=X_t-\\widehat\\mu_t$;\n",
        "3. forecast $\\widehat Y_{t+m}$ using a stationary model;\n",
        "4. add back the forecasted trend/seasonal component.\n",
        "\n",
        "If we difference the data, then we must invert differencing after forecasting. For example, if\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "Z_t=\\nabla X_t=X_t-X_{t-1},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and we forecast $\\widehat Z_{n+1|n},\\ldots,\\widehat Z_{n+m|n}$, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat X_{n+m|n}=X_n+\\sum_{j=1}^m\\widehat Z_{n+j|n}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## Common mistake\n",
        "Students often forecast differenced data and forget to return to the original scale. A forecast for $\\nabla X_t$ is not directly a forecast for $X_t$.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6.23 Forecasting and modern machine learning\n",
        "\n",
        "The best linear predictor is the classical foundation of forecasting. Modern machine learning generalizes it in several directions.\n",
        "\n",
        "| Classical forecasting object | Modern ML analogue |\n",
        "|---|---|\n",
        "| $\\widehat X_{t+1|t}=\\sum_j a_jX_{t+1-j}$ | linear layer on lag features |\n",
        "| AR($p$) | fixed-window autoregressive neural model |\n",
        "| MA($\\infty$) impulse response | convolutional filter over past shocks/features |\n",
        "| recursive prediction | recurrent hidden-state update |\n",
        "| covariance projection | learned representation/projection |\n",
        "| Gaussian forecast interval | probabilistic neural forecast |\n",
        "\n",
        "A windowed neural network forecast has the form\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\widehat X_{t+1|t}=f_\\Theta(X_t,X_{t-1},\\ldots,X_{t-p+1}),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $f_\\Theta$ is nonlinear and learned from data. This is a nonlinear extension of the best linear predictor.\n",
        "\n",
        "However, the same rule remains: the input window must only use past information.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6.24 AI-assisted study: useful prompts and guardrails\n",
        "\n",
        "AI tools can help you learn forecasting theory, but only if you ask for verifiable work.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Prompt 1: Derivation check\n",
        "\n",
        "> I derived the best linear predictor equations for $X_{n+1}$ from $X_n,\\ldots,X_1$. Check whether the orthogonality equations imply $\\Gamma_n\\phi_n=\\gamma_n$. Explain every index carefully and identify possible off-by-one errors.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Prompt 2: Code review for leakage\n",
        "\n",
        "> Review this time-series forecasting code. Check whether any future observations enter the training data, feature construction, scaling, or validation procedure. Mark every possible source of data leakage.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Prompt 3: Model interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "> I fitted an AR(2) model with coefficients $\\phi_1$ and $\\phi_2$. Explain how to compute one-step and multi-step forecasts recursively. Then explain how the characteristic roots affect the shape of the forecast path.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Prompt 4: Forecast interval explanation\n",
        "\n",
        "> Explain the difference between a confidence interval for a parameter and a forecast interval for a future observation in an AR(1) model. Use formulas and a simple numerical example.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## AI guardrail\n",
        "Do not accept an AI-generated forecast workflow unless it explicitly states the forecast origin, the training window, the prediction horizon, and how transformations are inverted. Without those details, the answer may be mathematically correct but operationally wrong.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6.25 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Using future data in features.** A rolling mean centered at time $t$ may use future values. Use past-only rolling features for forecasting.\n",
        "2. **Random train-test split.** Random splits destroy time order and usually create leakage.\n",
        "3. **Confusing fitted values with forecasts.** Fitted values use the data used to estimate the model. Forecasts predict future unseen values.\n",
        "4. **Ignoring forecast horizon.** A one-step model may perform well but fail for long horizons.\n",
        "5. **Forgetting mean adjustment.** If $E(X_t)=\\mu$, forecast deviations from $\\mu$, then add $\\mu$ back.\n",
        "6. **Forgetting to invert transformations.** Log transforms and differencing must be inverted carefully.\n",
        "7. **Reporting point forecasts only.** Forecast uncertainty is part of the model output.\n",
        "8. **Assuming linear prediction is always optimal.** Linear prediction is optimal under Gaussian assumptions, but nonlinear dependence may require nonlinear methods.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6.26 Mini project: classical forecasting report\n",
        "\n",
        "Choose one real or simulated time series and produce a short forecasting report.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Requirements\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Plot the series and describe trend, seasonality, outliers, and variance changes.\n",
        "2. Choose a stationary transformation or justify why none is needed.\n",
        "3. Fit at least two forecasting models:\n",
        "   - a naive or persistence baseline;\n",
        "   - an AR or ARMA-type model.\n",
        "4. Use chronological train/test splitting.\n",
        "5. Compare one-step and multi-step forecasts.\n",
        "6. Report RMSE or MAE and include forecast intervals when possible.\n",
        "7. Include a paragraph explaining whether your model uses only past information.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Suggested datasets\n",
        "\n",
        "- daily temperature;\n",
        "- electricity demand;\n",
        "- S&P 500 returns;\n",
        "- airline passengers after log transform;\n",
        "- simulated AR(2) with complex roots;\n",
        "- generated seasonal-plus-AR residual data.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6.27 Exercises\n",
        "\n",
        "### Conceptual exercises\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Explain why white noise is difficult to forecast even though its distribution is easy to describe.\n",
        "2. What does it mean for a forecast error to be orthogonal to the prediction variables?\n",
        "3. Why is conditional expectation the best mean-square predictor?\n",
        "4. Why is the best linear predictor especially important for Gaussian time series?\n",
        "5. Explain the difference between $\\widehat X_{t+1|t}$ and $\\widehat X_{t+5|t}$.\n",
        "6. Why does forecast uncertainty generally increase with horizon?\n",
        "\n",
        "### Mathematical exercises\n",
        "\n",
        "7. Let $X_t$ be zero-mean stationary with autocovariance $\\gamma(h)$. Derive the best linear predictor of $X_2$ from $X_1$ and compute its MSPE.\n",
        "8. Derive $\\Gamma_2\\phi_2=\\gamma_2$ explicitly for predicting $X_3$ from $X_2$ and $X_1$.\n",
        "9. For AR(1), derive the $m$-step forecast and forecast error variance.\n",
        "10. For AR(2), write the recursive formulas for $\\widehat X_{t+1|t}$, $\\widehat X_{t+2|t}$, and $\\widehat X_{t+3|t}$.\n",
        "11. For a causal ARMA process $X_t=\\sum_{j=0}^\\infty\\psi_jW_{t-j}$, derive the formula\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{MSPE}(m)=\\sigma_w^2\\sum_{j=0}^{m-1}\\psi_j^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "12. Suppose $X_t$ has mean $\\mu$. Derive the centered form of the best linear predictor and explain why centering simplifies the equations.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Python exercises\n",
        "\n",
        "13. Simulate an AR(1) process with $\\phi=0.9$. Compare one-step rolling forecasts with $\\phi$ known and with $\\phi$ estimated recursively.\n",
        "14. Simulate an AR(2) process with complex roots. Plot the forecast path from a large positive starting value.\n",
        "15. Implement the covariance matrix $\\Gamma_n$ for a given autocovariance function and solve for BLP coefficients.\n",
        "16. Estimate an AR(1) model using only the training set. Forecast the test set recursively and compute RMSE.\n",
        "17. Compare random train/test splitting with chronological splitting on a simulated AR(1). Explain why the random split is misleading.\n",
        "18. Use bootstrap simulation to estimate empirical forecast intervals for an AR(1) and compare them with the Gaussian formula.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6.28 Chapter checklist\n",
        "\n",
        "You are ready to move on when you can:\n",
        "\n",
        "- state the forecasting problem using $X_{n+m}$ and $\\mathcal F_n$;\n",
        "- explain conditional expectation as the MMSE predictor;\n",
        "- derive the orthogonality equations for best linear prediction;\n",
        "- write $\\Gamma_n\\phi_n=\\gamma_n$ and interpret every term;\n",
        "- compute the MSPE formula;\n",
        "- forecast AR(1) and AR($p$) models recursively;\n",
        "- explain why MA and ARMA forecasting depends on innovations;\n",
        "- compute forecast error variance from $\\psi$ weights;\n",
        "- construct forecast intervals under Gaussian assumptions;\n",
        "- evaluate forecasting code for time leakage;\n",
        "- describe how classical forecasting ideas connect to ML sequence models.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 6.29 Key takeaways\n",
        "\n",
        "Best linear prediction is the mathematical core of classical forecasting. The forecast is a projection of the future value onto the space spanned by the observed past. The residual is orthogonal to all information used in the prediction. For stationary processes, this projection is determined by the autocovariance function. For AR and ARMA models, the same theory leads to simple recursive forecasts and explicit formulas for forecast uncertainty. These ideas remain central in modern machine learning, where lag windows, convolutional filters, recurrent states, and attention mechanisms are nonlinear extensions of the same basic goal: use the past to predict the future without leaking information from the future."
      ],
